---
import Layout from "../../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import "../../../styles/global.css";

const breadcrumbSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
  "itemListElement": [
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://takehomepay.nz/" },
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Guides", "item": "https://takehomepay.nz/guides/" },
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 3, "name": "NZ Tax Codes Explained", "item": "https://takehomepay.nz/guides/tax-codes-nz/" }
  ]
};

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I know which tax code to use in New Zealand?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "For your main (highest-paying) job, use M if you do not qualify for the IETC, or ME if you do. If you have a student loan, add SL to get MSL or MESL. For a second job, use S if your combined income is $15,600 or less, SH if between $15,601 and $53,500, ST if between $53,501 and $78,100, or the appropriate higher rate code. IRD provides an online tax code finder tool at ird.govt.nz to help you determine the correct code."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What happens if I use the wrong tax code?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "If you use the wrong tax code, you may pay too much or too little tax during the year. IRD will reconcile your total income after the tax year ends (31 March) and either refund overpaid tax or send you a bill for underpaid tax. While the end result is the same, using the correct code avoids the inconvenience of an unexpected bill or having money tied up in overpaid tax throughout the year."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the ME tax code and who should use it?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The ME tax code is for primary employment where you are entitled to the Independent Earner Tax Credit (IETC). You should use ME if your total annual income is between $24,000 and $48,000, you do not receive any income-tested benefits or Working for Families tax credits, and you do not receive NZ Superannuation. The IETC provides up to $520 per year in tax savings, which is applied automatically through the ME code."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<Layout
  title="NZ Tax Codes Explained: M, ME, S, SH, ST & Secondary Income | TakeHomePay.nz"
  description="A plain-English guide to New Zealand tax codes. Learn the difference between M, ME, MSL, S, SH, ST, and student loan codes, and find out which one you should use."
  canonical="/guides/tax-codes-nz/"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbSchema)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />

  <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-primary to-primary-light py-12">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 text-center text-white">
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold mb-4 text-white">NZ Tax Codes Explained: M, ME, S, SH, ST & Secondary Income</h1>
      <p class="text-lg text-white/90">Pick the right tax code to avoid underpaying or overpaying PAYE tax in New Zealand.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="py-12 sm:py-16">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb" class="mb-8 text-sm text-text-muted">
        <ol class="flex items-center gap-2 flex-wrap">
          <li><a href="/" class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">Home</a></li>
          <li class="before:content-['/'] before:mx-2 before:text-border"><a href="/guides/" class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">Guides</a></li>
          <li class="before:content-['/'] before:mx-2 before:text-border font-medium text-text">NZ Tax Codes Explained</li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>
          Your tax code is a short letter combination that tells your employer how much PAYE tax and other deductions to withhold from your pay. Getting your tax code right is one of the simplest but most important things you can do to avoid tax problems in New Zealand. Use the wrong code and you could end up with an unexpected bill from Inland Revenue (IRD) at the end of the year, or alternatively you might overpay tax and have your money tied up unnecessarily until IRD processes your refund.
        </p>

        <p>
          This guide walks through every commonly used tax code in New Zealand, explains when each one applies, and helps you figure out exactly which code you should be using for your situation. Whether you have a single job, multiple jobs, a student loan, or qualify for the Independent Earner Tax Credit, there is a specific code for you.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">What Is a Tax Code?</h2>

        <p>
          A tax code is a declaration you make to each employer or payer about your tax circumstances. When you start a new job, your employer will ask you to complete a Tax code declaration form (IR330) where you nominate the appropriate tax code. Your employer uses this code to calculate how much PAYE income tax, ACC Earner's Levy, and student loan repayments to deduct from your pay each period.
        </p>

        <p>
          Tax codes are necessary because New Zealand's progressive tax system applies different rates to different levels of income. Your primary employer needs to know that they should apply the full progressive scale (including the lowest brackets) to your pay, while any secondary employers should tax your income at a flat rate appropriate to your total income level. Without tax codes, the system would not know how to allocate the tax-free portions and lower-rate brackets correctly across multiple income sources.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Primary Employment Tax Codes</h2>

        <p>
          Primary employment tax codes are for your main job, which should be the one where you earn the most income. You can only use one primary tax code across all your employment. The key primary codes are:
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-primary mt-8 mb-3">M - Primary Employment</h3>

        <p>
          The M code is the standard tax code for your primary job. It applies the progressive PAYE tax scale, starting with the lowest bracket of 10.5 percent on your first $15,600 of income and progressing through the higher brackets as your income increases. Use the M code if you have one job and do not qualify for the Independent Earner Tax Credit (IETC), or if you are not sure whether you qualify.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-primary mt-8 mb-3">ME - Primary Employment with IETC</h3>

        <p>
          The ME code works exactly like the M code but also applies the Independent Earner Tax Credit, which reduces your PAYE by up to $10 per week ($520 per year). You should use ME if all of the following apply: your annual income from all sources is between $24,000 and $48,000; you do not receive any income-tested government benefits; you do not receive Working for Families tax credits; and you do not receive NZ Superannuation. The IETC is worth up to $520 per year for incomes between $24,000 and $44,000, and reduces by 13 cents per dollar between $44,000 and $48,000.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Student Loan Tax Codes</h2>

        <p>
          If you have an active student loan, your tax code must include the letters "SL" to ensure your employer deducts student loan repayments from your pay. The repayment rate is 12 percent on income above the annual threshold of $22,828. The student loan variants of the primary codes are:
        </p>

        <p>
          <strong>MSL</strong> - Primary employment with a student loan. Use this if you have a student loan and do not qualify for the IETC. <strong>MESL</strong> - Primary employment with a student loan and IETC entitlement. Use this if you qualify for the IETC and have a student loan.
        </p>

        <p>
          For secondary employment with a student loan, the codes are SSL, SHSL, and STSL, corresponding to the S, SH, and ST codes with student loan deductions added. We cover the secondary codes in detail below.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Secondary Employment Tax Codes</h2>

        <p>
          If you have more than one job, all jobs other than your primary one must use a secondary tax code. Secondary codes apply a flat withholding rate rather than the progressive scale, because the progressive brackets are already being applied by your primary employer. The three main secondary codes are:
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-primary mt-8 mb-3">S - Secondary at 17.5%</h3>

        <p>
          Use the S code if your total annual income from all jobs combined is $15,600 or less. This rate of 17.5 percent may result in slight over-deduction if your total income truly falls within the lowest bracket, but any excess is refunded after the end of the tax year.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-primary mt-8 mb-3">SH - Secondary at 30%</h3>

        <p>
          Use the SH code if your total annual income from all jobs is between $15,601 and $53,500. This is the most commonly used secondary code, as many people with a second job fall into this income range. The 30 percent rate aims to approximate the marginal rate that would apply to the secondary income if it were added on top of the primary income.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-primary mt-8 mb-3">ST - Secondary at 33%</h3>

        <p>
          Use the ST code if your total annual income from all jobs is between $53,501 and $78,100. This higher rate reflects the fact that the secondary income effectively falls in a higher tax bracket when combined with primary income.
        </p>

        <p>
          For incomes above $78,100, additional secondary codes apply: SA at 33 percent for combined income between $78,101 and $180,000, and SB at 39 percent for combined income above $180,000. These higher-rate codes ensure that the tax withheld on secondary income closely matches the actual tax liability.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Complete Tax Code Reference Table</h2>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
          <table class="w-full border-collapse border border-border text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="bg-surface-alt">
                <th class="border border-border px-4 py-3 text-left font-bold text-primary">Code</th>
                <th class="border border-border px-4 py-3 text-left font-bold text-primary">Type</th>
                <th class="border border-border px-4 py-3 text-left font-bold text-primary">When to Use</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3 font-mono">M</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Primary</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Main job, no IETC</td></tr>
              <tr class="bg-surface"><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3 font-mono">ME</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Primary</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Main job with IETC ($24k-$48k, no benefits)</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3 font-mono">MSL</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Primary + SL</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Main job with student loan</td></tr>
              <tr class="bg-surface"><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3 font-mono">MESL</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Primary + SL</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Main job with IETC and student loan</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3 font-mono">S</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Secondary</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Second job, total income up to $15,600</td></tr>
              <tr class="bg-surface"><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3 font-mono">SH</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Secondary</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Second job, total income $15,601-$53,500</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3 font-mono">ST</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Secondary</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Second job, total income $53,501-$78,100</td></tr>
              <tr class="bg-surface"><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3 font-mono">SA</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Secondary</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Second job, total income $78,101-$180,000</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3 font-mono">SB</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Secondary</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">Second job, total income above $180,000</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">How to Choose the Right Secondary Code</h2>

        <p>
          Choosing the correct secondary tax code requires you to estimate your total annual income from all sources. Add up your expected earnings from your primary job and all secondary jobs for the tax year (1 April to 31 March). Based on this total, select the secondary code from the table above that corresponds to your total income range.
        </p>

        <p>
          If your income changes during the year, for instance if you get a pay rise, change your hours, or start or stop a second job, you should reassess your tax code. You can change your tax code at any time by completing a new IR330 form and giving it to your employer. Getting the code right throughout the year minimises the chance of an end-of-year tax bill.
        </p>

        <p>
          A common mistake is using the S code (17.5 percent) on a secondary job when the combined income puts you in the SH or ST bracket. This leads to under-deduction of tax during the year, and IRD will send you a bill after the end of the tax year for the shortfall. While you can set up a payment arrangement with IRD, it is far easier to use the correct code from the outset.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Special Tax Codes</h2>

        <p>
          In some circumstances, the standard tax codes may not result in the right amount of tax being deducted. If you consistently over-pay or under-pay tax, you can apply to IRD for a special tax code (also known as a tailored tax code). IRD will assess your situation and issue a specific rate that your employer should use instead of the standard code.
        </p>

        <p>
          Special tax codes are particularly useful for people with significant tax credits, multiple income sources, or income that varies considerably throughout the year. For example, if you earn commission that fluctuates month to month, a special tax code based on your expected annual income can help smooth out your tax deductions and avoid large refunds or bills at year end.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Changing Your Tax Code</h2>

        <p>
          You can change your tax code at any time by completing an IR330 form and giving it to your employer. Common reasons for changing your tax code include starting a second job, leaving a second job, qualifying for or losing IETC eligibility, repaying your student loan in full, or a significant change in your expected annual income.
        </p>

        <p>
          Your employer must apply the new tax code from the next pay period after they receive your updated IR330 form. They cannot backdate a tax code change, so if you have been on the wrong code for several months, the over-deduction or under-deduction from those months will be reconciled in your end-of-year assessment.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">No Notification Rate</h2>

        <p>
          If you start a new job and do not provide a tax code declaration (IR330) to your employer, they are required to deduct tax at the "no notification" rate of 45 percent. This is the highest withholding rate and is designed to encourage employees to provide their correct tax code promptly. Any over-deduction at the 45 percent rate will be refunded after your end-of-year assessment, but in the meantime your take home pay will be significantly reduced.
        </p>

        <p>
          To avoid the no notification rate, make sure you complete and return the IR330 form to your employer before or on your first day of work. If you are unsure which tax code to use, the IRD website has an interactive tax code finder tool that asks a series of questions about your circumstances and recommends the appropriate code.
        </p>

        <!-- FAQ Section -->
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="space-y-4 not-prose">
          <details class="border border-border rounded-xl p-4 group">
            <summary class="font-bold text-primary cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
              How do I know which tax code to use in New Zealand?
              <span class="text-accent transition-transform group-open:rotate-45 text-xl">+</span>
            </summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-text leading-relaxed">For your main (highest-paying) job, use M if you do not qualify for the IETC, or ME if you do. If you have a student loan, add SL to get MSL or MESL. For a second job, use S if your combined income is $15,600 or less, SH if between $15,601 and $53,500, ST if between $53,501 and $78,100, or the appropriate higher rate code. IRD provides an online tax code finder tool at ird.govt.nz to help you determine the correct code.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="border border-border rounded-xl p-4 group">
            <summary class="font-bold text-primary cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
              What happens if I use the wrong tax code?
              <span class="text-accent transition-transform group-open:rotate-45 text-xl">+</span>
            </summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-text leading-relaxed">If you use the wrong tax code, you may pay too much or too little tax during the year. IRD will reconcile your total income after the tax year ends (31 March) and either refund overpaid tax or send you a bill for underpaid tax. While the end result is the same, using the correct code avoids the inconvenience of an unexpected bill or having money tied up in overpaid tax throughout the year.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="border border-border rounded-xl p-4 group">
            <summary class="font-bold text-primary cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
              What is the ME tax code and who should use it?
              <span class="text-accent transition-transform group-open:rotate-45 text-xl">+</span>
            </summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-text leading-relaxed">The ME tax code is for primary employment where you are entitled to the Independent Earner Tax Credit (IETC). You should use ME if your total annual income is between $24,000 and $48,000, you do not receive any income-tested benefits or Working for Families tax credits, and you do not receive NZ Superannuation. The IETC provides up to $520 per year in tax savings, which is applied automatically through the ME code.</p>
          </details>
        </div>

        <!-- Related Tools -->
        <div class="mt-10 border border-border rounded-xl p-6 bg-surface">
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">Related Tools & Guides</h2>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
            <li><a href="/" class="text-accent hover:underline">NZ Salary Calculator</a> - Calculate your take home pay with the correct deductions</li>
            <li><a href="/guides/paye-tax-nz/" class="text-accent hover:underline">PAYE Tax in New Zealand</a> - How the progressive tax brackets work</li>
            <li><a href="/guides/secondary-income-tax/" class="text-accent hover:underline">Secondary Income Tax</a> - In-depth guide to tax on multiple jobs</li>
            <li><a href="/guides/student-loan-repayment-nz/" class="text-accent hover:underline">Student Loan Repayment</a> - How student loan tax codes affect deductions</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Sources -->
        <div class="mt-8 border-t border-border pt-6">
          <h2 class="text-lg font-bold text-primary mb-3">Sources</h2>
          <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm text-text-muted">
            <li><a href="https://www.ird.govt.nz/income-tax/income-tax-for-individuals/tax-codes-and-tax-rates-for-individuals/tax-codes-for-individuals" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:underline">IRD - Tax codes for individuals</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.ird.govt.nz/income-tax/income-tax-for-individuals/tax-codes-and-tax-rates-for-individuals/work-out-your-tax-code" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:underline">IRD - Work out your tax code</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.employment.govt.nz/hours-and-wages/pay/taxes-and-deductions/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:underline">Employment New Zealand - Taxes and deductions</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
